aica |journal=Caribbean Quarterly |volume=26 |number=4 |year=1980 |pages=32\u201341 |jstor=40795020 |ref=|doi=10.1080/00086495.1980.11829315 }}\n\n: {{cite journal |last=Pollard |first=Velma |title=The Social History of Dread Talk |journal=Caribbean Quarterly |volume=28 |issue=4 |year=1982 |pages=117\u2013140 |jstor=40653574 |ref=|doi=10.1080/00086495.1982.11829332 }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Pollard |first=Velma |title=Dread Talk: The Language of the Rastafari |year=2000 |edition=revised |publisher=McGill-Queen's University Press |isbn=978-0773520301 |ref= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/dreadtalklanguag00poll }}\n\n: {{cite journal |last=Price |first=Charles |title=Social Change and the Development and Co-Optation of a Black Antisystemic Identity: The Case of Rastafarians in Jamaica |year=2003 |journal=Identity |volume=3 |issue=1 |pages=9\u201327 |doi=10.1207/S1532706XID0301_02 |ref=}}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Price |first=Charles |year=2009 |title=Becoming Rasta: Origins of Rastafari Identity in Jamaica |publisher=New York University Press |isbn=978-0814767474 |ref=}}\n\n: {{cite journal |last=Price |first=Charles |title=The Cultural Production of a Black Messiah: Ethiopianism and the Rastafari |journal=Journal of Africana Religions |volume=2 |number=3 |year=2014 |pages=418\u2013433 |ref=}}\n\n: {{cite journal |last=Savishinsky |first=Neil J. |title=Rastafari in the Promised Land: The Spread of a Jamaican Socioreligious Movement among the Youth of West Africa |journal=African Studies Review |volume=37 |number=3 |year=1994 |pages=19\u201350 |jstor=524901 |ref=|doi=10.2307/524901 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/99e4232c131ab3d268f71b79e1ca3f6e6e4d7578 }}\n\n: {{cite journal |last=Savishinsky |first=Neil J. |title= Transnational Popular Culture and the Global Spread of the Jamaican Rastafarian Movement|journal= NWIG: New West Indian Guide / Nieuwe West-Indische Gids|volume=68 |issue=3 |year=1994 |pages=259\u2013281 |jstor=41849614 |ref=|