ueowl", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGender roles and sexuality:correcting year in citation.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rastafari"}
{"title_page": "Transformer (machine learning model)", "text_new": "The '''Transformer''' is a [[Deep learning|deep]] [[machine learning]] model introduced in 2017, used primarily in the field of [[natural language processing]] (NLP).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite arxiv|last=Polosukhin|first=Illia|last2=Kaiser|first2=Lukasz|last3=Gomez|first3=Aidan N.|last4=Jones|first4=Llion|last5=Uszkoreit|first5=Jakob|last6=Parmar|first6=Niki|last7=Shazeer|first7=Noam|last8=Vaswani|first8=Ashish|date=2017-06-12|title=Attention Is All You Need|eprint=1706.03762|class=cs.CL}}</ref> Like [[recurrent neural networks]] (RNNs), Transformers are designed to handle ordered sequences of data, such as natural language, for various tasks such as [[Statistical machine translation|machine translation]] and [[Automatic summarization|text summarization]]. However, unlike RNNs, Transformers do not require that the sequence be processed in order. So, if the data in question is natural language, the Transformer does not need to process the beginning of a sentence before it processes the end. Due to this feature, the Transformer allows for much more [[Parallel computing|parallelization]] than RNNs during training.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSince their introduction, Transformers have become the basic building block of most state-of-the-art architectures in NLP, replacing gated recurrent neural network models such as the [[long short-term memory]] (LSTM) in many cases. Since the Transformer architecture facilitates more parallelization during training computations, it has enabled training on much more data than was possible before it was introduced. This led to the development of [[Transfer learning|pretrained systems]] such as [[BERT (language model)|BERT]] (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) and [[OpenAI#GPT-2|GPT-2]], which have been trained with huge amounts of general language data prior to being released, and can then be fine-tune trained to specific language tasks.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://ai.googleblog.com/2018/11/open-sourcing-bert-state-of-art-pre.html|title=Open Sourcing BERT: State-of-the-Art Pre-training for Natural Language Processing|website=Google AI Blog|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://openai.com/blog/better-language-models/|title=Better Language Models and Their Implications|date=2019-02-14|website=OpenAI|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe primary motivations for the development of the Transformer were to reduce path lengths, thereby making long-range dependencies in sequences easier to learn, and to allow for more parallelization than previous models such as [[recurrent neural network]]s and [[convolutional neural network]]s (CNNs).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://mchromiak.github.io/articles/2017/Sep/12/Transformer-Attention-is-all-you-need/#.Xax6nOhKiUm|title=The Transformer \u2013 Attention is all you need.|last=Chromiak|first=Micha\u0142|date=2017-09-12|website=Micha\u0142 Chromiak's blog|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref> While the path length in RNNs and CNNs is linear and logarithmic respectively, it is constant in a Transformer, greatly facilitating training. Additionally, the Transformer does not rely as heavily on the prohibitive sequential nature of input data as do CNNs and especially RNNs.\n\n=== Recurrent Neural Networks ===\nVarious architectures of recurrent neural networks have been successful in performing tasks relating to sequences, due to their ability to process inputs of arbitrary length, rather than being restricted to fixed length inputs like those of [[multilayer perceptron]]s.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://karpathy.github.io/2015/05/21/rnn-effectiveness/|title=The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Recurrent Neural Networks|website=karpathy.github.io|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref> RNNs operate by processing inputs sequentially and retaining a hidden vector between iterations which is constantly used and modified throughout the sequence. An RNN can be interpreted as a program which uses a hidden vector as its memory.<ref name=\":4\" /> Theoretically, RNNs are able to model arbitrarily complicated programs due to their Turing-completeness, just as perceptrons are able to model arbitrarily complicated functions, but in practice, RNNs suffer from a variant of the [[vanishing gradient problem]], making it extremely difficult for them to learn long-range dependencies in sequences.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://colah.github.io/posts/2015-08-Understanding-LSTMs/|title=Understanding LSTM Networks -- colah's blog|website=colah.github.io|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bengio|first=Y.|last2=Simard|first2=P.|last3=Frasconi|first3=P.|date=March 1994|title=Learning long-term dependencies with gradient descent is difficult|journal=IEEE Transactions on Neural Networks|volume=5|issue=2|pages=157\u2013166|doi=10.1109/72.279181|pmid=18267787|issn=1045-9227}}</ref>\n\n[[Long short-term memory|Long short term memory]] (LSTM) models, a variant of RNNs, attempt to alleviate this issue by choosing very specific operations to perform in the recurrent portion of the network.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hochreiter|first=Sepp|last2=Schmidhuber|first2=J\u00fcrgen|date=November 1997|title=Long Short-Term Memory|journal=Neural Computation|volume=9|issue=8|pages=1735\u20131780|doi=10.1162/neco.1997.9.8.1735|pmid=9377276|issn=0899-7667}}</ref> LSTMs make use of a cell state which only passes through linear operations in the recurrent portion, allowing information to pass through relatively unchanged with each iteration.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nAlthough RNNs are able to handle long-range dependencies in arbitrary length sequences, they still struggle with this issue, and are not easy to parallelize due to the sequential nature of their computation.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Convolutional Neural Networks ===\n[[Autoregressive model|Autoregressive]] convolutional neural networks can handle long-range dependencies through dilated convolutions such that the path length is logarithmic.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite arxiv|last=Oord|first=Aaron van den|last2=Dieleman|first2=Sander|last3=Zen|first3=Heiga|last4=Simonyan|first4=Karen|last5=Vinyals|first5=Oriol|last6=Graves|first6=Alex|last7=Kalchbrenner|first7=Nal|last8=Senior|first8=Andrew|last9=Kavukcuoglu|first9=Koray|date=2016-09-12|title=WaveNet: A Generative Model for Raw Audio|eprint=1609.03499|class=cs.SD}}</ref> CNNs also allow for parallelization within layers.\n\n== Architecture ==\nThe Transformer consists of two main components: a set of encoders chained together and a set of decoders chained together. The function of each encoder is to process its input vectors to generate what are known as encodings, which contain information about the parts of the inputs which are relevant to each other. It passes its set of generated encodings to the next encoder as inputs. Each decoder does the opposite, taking all the encodings and processing them, using their incorporated contextual information to generate an output sequence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indico.io/blog/sequence-modeling-neural-networks-part2-attention-models/|title=Sequence Modeling with Neural Networks (Part 2): Attention Models|date=2016-04-18|website=Indico|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> To achieve this, each encoder and decoder makes use of an attention mechanism, which for each input, weighs the relevance of every input and draws information from them accordingly when producing the output.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://jalammar.github.io/illustrated-transformer/|title=The Illustrated Transformer|last=Alammar|first=Jay|website=jalammar.github.io|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> Each decoder also has an additional attention mechanism which draws information from the outputs of previous decoders, before the decoder draws information from the encodings. Both the encoders and decoders have a final [[Feedforward neural network|feed-forward neural network]] for additional processing of the outputs, and also contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Encoder ===\nEach encoder consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward neural network. The self-attention mechanism takes in a set of input encodings from the previous encoder and weighs their relevance to each other to generate a set of output encodings. The feed-forward neural network then further processes each output encoding individually. These output encodings are finally passed to the next encoder as its input, as well as the decoders.\n\nThe first encoder takes positional information and [[Word embedding|embeddings]] of the input sequence as its input, rather than encodings. The positional information is necessary for the Transformer to make use of the order of the sequence, because no other part of the Transformer makes use of this.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Decoder ===\nEach decoder consists of three major components: a self-attention mechanism, an attention mechanism over the encodings, and a feed-forward neural network. The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nLike the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings. Since the transformer should not use the current or future output to predict an output though, the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.<ref name=\":0\" /> The last decoder is followed by a final [[Matrix multiplication|linear transformation]] and [[Softmax function|softmax layer]], to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.\n\n=== Scaled Dot-Product Attention ===\nThe purpose of an attention mechanism is to use a set of encodings to incorporate context into a sequence.<ref name=\":1\" /> An attention mechanism takes a set of queries and a set of key-value pairs in order to generate an output, where the queries are generated by linear transformations of the vectors in the sequence, and the keys and values are generated by linear transformations of the encodings.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://lilianweng.github.io/2018/06/24/attention-attention.html|title=Attention? Attention!|date=2018-06-24|website=Lil'Log|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> Self-attention refers to the situation where the queries, keys, and values are all created using encodings of the sequence.<ref name=\":1\" /> Scaled dot-product attention multiples the queries by the keys, divides by a scaling factor and takes the softmax, and finally uses the result to compute a weighted sum of the values corresponding to the keys, generating an encoding of the original sequence.<ref name=\":0\" /> If <math>\\mathbf{Q}</math>, <math>\\mathbf{K}</math>, and <math>\\mathbf{V}</math> are the matrices containing the queries, keys, and values respectively and <math>n</math> is the dimension of the queries and keys, then the output of this attention mechanism is:<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{Attention}(\\mathbf{Q}, \\mathbf{K}, \\mathbf{V}) = \\text{softmax}(\\frac{\\mathbf{Q}\\mathbf{K}^T}{\\sqrt{n}})\\mathbf{V}\n\\end{align}\n</math>\n\nIn practice, it is useful to implement several attention mechanisms in parallel and then combine the resulting encodings together in a process called multi-head attention.\n\n== Training ==\nTransformers typically undergo [[semi-supervised learning]] involving [[Unsupervised learning|unsupervised]] pretraining followed by [[Supervised learning|supervised]] fine-tuning. Pretraining is typically done on a much larger dataset than fine-tuning, due to the restricted availability of labeled training data. Tasks for pretraining and fine-tuning commonly include:\n\n* next-sentence prediction<ref name=\":6\" />\n*[[question answering]]<ref name=\":7\" />\n*[[Natural-language understanding|reading comprehension]]\n*[[sentiment analysis]]<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alex|last2=Singh|first2=Amanpreet|last3=Michael|first3=Julian|last4=Hill|first4=Felix|last5=Levy|first5=Omer|last6=Bowman|first6=Samuel|date=2018|title=GLUE: A Multi-Task Benchmark and Analysis Platform for Natural Language Understanding|journal=Proceedings of the 2018 EMNLP Workshop BlackboxNLP: Analyzing and Interpreting Neural Networks for NLP|pages=353\u2013355|location=Stroudsburg, PA, USA|publisher=Association for Computational Linguistics|doi=10.18653/v1/w18-5446|bibcode=2018arXiv180407461W|arxiv=1804.07461}}</ref>\n*[[Text Summaries|paraphrasing]]<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Applications ==\nThe Transformer finds most of its applications in the field of [[natural language processing]] (NLP), for example the tasks of [[machine translation]] and [[Time series|time series prediction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/inside-machine-learning/what-is-a-transformer-d07dd1fbec04|title=What is a Transformer?|last=Allard|first=Maxime|date=2019-07-01|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>  Many pretrained models such as GPT-2, BERT, XLNet, and RoBERTa demonstrate the ability of Transformers to perform a wide variety of such NLP-related tasks, and have the potential to find real-world applications.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=XLNet: Generalized Autoregressive Pretraining for Language Understanding|last=Yang, Zhilin Dai, Zihang Yang, Yiming Carbonell, Jaime Salakhutdinov, Ruslan Le, Quoc V.|date=2019-06-19|oclc=1106350082}}</ref> These may include:\n\n* [[machine translation]]\n* [[Automatic summarization|document summarization]]\n* [[Natural-language generation|document generation]]\n* [[Named-entity recognition|named entity recognition]] (NER)<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@datamonsters/artificial-neural-networks-in-natural-language-processing-bcf62aa9151a|title=10 Applications of Artificial Neural Networks in Natural Language Processing|last=Monsters|first=Data|date=2017-09-26|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n* [[speech recognition]]<ref name=\":9\" />\n* [[sequence analysis | biological sequence analysis]] <ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1101/622803|title=Biological structure and function emerge from scaling unsupervised learning to 250 million protein sequences|year=2019|last1=Rives|first1=Alexander|last2=Goyal|first2=Siddharth|last3=Meier|first3=Joshua|last4=Guo|first4=Demi|last5=Ott|first5=Myle|last6=Zitnick|first6=C. Lawrence|last7=Ma|first7=Jerry|last8=Fergus|first8=Rob}}</ref>\n\n== References ==<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n<!-- Use the format: * [http://www.example.com/ example.com] -->\n<!--- Categories --->\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Long Short Term Memory}}\n[[Category:Artificial neural networks]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Transformer''' is a [[Deep learning|deep]] [[machine learning]] model introduced in 2017, used primarily in the field of [[natural language processing]] (NLP).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite arxiv|last=Polosukhin|first=Illia|last2=Kaiser|first2=Lukasz|last3=Gomez|first3=Aidan N.|last4=Jones|first4=Llion|last5=Uszkoreit|first5=Jakob|last6=Parmar|first6=Niki|last7=Shazeer|first7=Noam|last8=Vaswani|first8=Ashish|date=2017-06-12|title=Attention Is All You Need|eprint=1706.03762|class=cs.CL}}</ref> Like [[recurrent neural networks]] (RNNs), Transformers are designed to handle ordered sequences of data, such as natural language, for various tasks such as [[Statistical machine translation|machine translation]] and [[Automatic summarization|text summarization]]. However, unlike RNNs, Transformers do not require that the sequence be processed in order. So, if the data in question is natural language, the Transformer does not need to process the beginning of a sentence before it processes the end. Due to this feature, the Transformer allows for much more [[Parallel computing|parallelization]] than RNNs during training.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSince their introduction, Transformers have become the basic building block of most state-of-the-art architectures in NLP, replacing gated recurrent neural network models such as the [[long short-term memory]] (LSTM) in many cases. Since the Transformer architecture facilitates more parallelization during training computations, it has enabled training on much more data than was possible before it was introduced. This led to the development of [[Transfer learning|pretrained systems]] such as [[BERT (language model)|BERT]] (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) and [[OpenAI#GPT-2|GPT-2]], which have been trained with huge amounts of general language data prior to being released, and can then be fine-tune trained to specific language tasks.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://ai.googleblog.com/2018/11/open-sourcing-bert-state-of-art-pre.html|title=Open Sourcing BERT: State-of-the-Art Pre-training for Natural Language Processing|website=Google AI Blog|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://openai.com/blog/better-language-models/|title=Better Language Models and Their Implications|date=2019-02-14|website=OpenAI|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe primary motivations for the development of the Transformer were to reduce path lengths, thereby making long-range dependencies in sequences easier to learn, and to allow for more parallelization than previous models such as [[recurrent neural network]]s and [[convolutional neural network]]s (CNNs).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://mchromiak.github.io/articles/2017/Sep/12/Transformer-Attention-is-all-you-need/#.Xax6nOhKiUm|title=The Transformer \u2013 Attention is all you need.|last=Chromiak|first=Micha\u0142|date=2017-09-12|website=Micha\u0142 Chromiak's blog|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref> While path lengths in RNNs and CNNs are linear and logarithmic respectively, it is constant in a Transformer, greatly facilitating training. Additionally, the Transformer does not rely as heavily on the prohibitive sequential nature of input data as do CNNs and especially RNNs.\n\n=== Recurrent Neural Networks ===\nVarious architectures of recurrent neural networks have been successful in performing tasks relating to sequences, due to their ability to process inputs of arbitrary length, rather than being restricted to fixed length inputs like those of [[multilayer perceptron]]s.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://karpathy.github.io/2015/05/21/rnn-effectiveness/|title=The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Recurrent Neural Networks|website=karpathy.github.io|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref> RNNs operate by processing inputs sequentially and retaining a hidden vector between iterations which is constantly used and modified throughout the sequence. An RNN can be interpreted as a program which uses a hidden vector as its memory.<ref name=\":4\" /> Theoretically, RNNs are able to model arbitrarily complicated programs due to their Turing-completeness, just as perceptrons are able to model arbitrarily complicated functions, but in practice, RNNs suffer from a variant of the [[vanishing gradient problem]], making it extremely difficult for them to learn long-range dependencies in sequences.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://colah.github.io/posts/2015-08-Understanding-LSTMs/|title=Understanding LSTM Networks -- colah's blog|website=colah.github.io|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bengio|first=Y.|last2=Simard|first2=P.|last3=Frasconi|first3=P.|date=March 1994|title=Learning long-term dependencies with gradient descent is difficult|journal=IEEE Transactions on Neural Networks|volume=5|issue=2|pages=157\u2013166|doi=10.1109/72.279181|pmid=18267787|issn=1045-9227}}</ref>\n\n[[Long short-term memory|Long short term memory]] (LSTM) models, a variant of RNNs, attempt to alleviate this issue by choosing very specific operations to perform in the recurrent portion of the network.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hochreiter|first=Sepp|last2=Schmidhuber|first2=J\u00fcrgen|date=November 1997|title=Long Short-Term Memory|journal=Neural Computation|volume=9|issue=8|pages=1735\u20131780|doi=10.1162/neco.1997.9.8.1735|pmid=9377276|issn=0899-7667}}</ref> LSTMs make use of a cell state which only passes through linear operations in the recurrent portion, allowing information to pass through relatively unchanged with each iteration.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nAlthough RNNs are able to handle long-range dependencies in arbitrary length sequences, they still struggle with this issue, and are not easy to parallelize due to the sequential nature of their computation.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Convolutional Neural Networks ===\n[[Autoregressive model|Autoregressive]] convolutional neural networks can handle long-range dependencies through dilated convolutions such that the path length is logarithmic.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite arxiv|last=Oord|first=Aaron van den|last2=Dieleman|first2=Sander|last3=Zen|first3=Heiga|last4=Simonyan|first4=Karen|last5=Vinyals|first5=Oriol|last6=Graves|first6=Alex|last7=Kalchbrenner|first7=Nal|last8=Senior|first8=Andrew|last9=Kavukcuoglu|first9=Koray|date=2016-09-12|title=WaveNet: A Generative Model for Raw Audio|eprint=1609.03499|class=cs.SD}}</ref> CNNs also allow for parallelization within layers.\n\n== Architecture ==\nThe Transformer consists of two main components: a set of encoders chained together and a set of decoders chained together. The function of each encoder is to process its input vectors to generate what are known as encodings, which contain information about the parts of the inputs which are relevant to each other. It passes its set of generated encodings to the next encoder as inputs. Each decoder does the opposite, taking all the encodings and processing them, using their incorporated contextual information to generate an output sequence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indico.io/blog/sequence-modeling-neural-networks-part2-attention-models/|title=Sequence Modeling with Neural Networks (Part 2): Attention Models|date=2016-04-18|website=Indico|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> To achieve this, each encoder and decoder makes use of an attention mechanism, which for each input, weighs the relevance of every input and draws information from them accordingly when producing the output.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://jalammar.github.io/illustrated-transformer/|title=The Illustrated Transformer|last=Alammar|first=Jay|website=jalammar.github.io|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> Each decoder also has an additional attention mechanism which draws information from the outputs of previous decoders, before the decoder draws information from the encodings. Both the encoders and decoders have a final [[Feedforward neural network|feed-forward neural network]] for additional processing of the outputs, and also contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Encoder ===\nEach encoder consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward neural network. The self-attention mechanism takes in a set of input encodings from the previous encoder and weighs their relevance to each other to generate a set of output encodings. The feed-forward neural network then further processes each output encoding individually. These output encodings are finally passed to the next encoder as its input, as well as the decoders.\n\nThe first encoder takes positional information and [[Word embedding|embeddings]] of the input sequence as its input, rather than encodings. The positional information is necessary for the Transformer to make use of the order of the sequence, because no other part of the Transformer makes use of this.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Decoder ===\nEach decoder consists of three major components: a self-attention mechanism, an attention mechanism over the encodings, and a feed-forward neural network. The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nLike the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings. Since the transformer should not use the current or future output to predict an output though, the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.<ref name=\":0\" /> The last decoder is followed by a final [[Matrix multiplication|linear transformation]] and [[Softmax function|softmax layer]], to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.\n\n=== Scaled Dot-Product Attention ===\nThe purpose of an attention mechanism is to use a set of encodings to incorporate context into a sequence.<ref name=\":1\" /> An attention mechanism takes a set of queries and a set of key-value pairs in order to generate an output, where the queries are generated by linear transformations of the vectors in the sequence, and the keys and values are generated by linear transformations of the encodings.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://lilianweng.github.io/2018/06/24/attention-attention.html|title=Attention? Attention!|date=2018-06-24|website=Lil'Log|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> Self-attention refers to the situation where the queries, keys, and values are all created using encodings of the sequence.<ref name=\":1\" /> Scaled dot-product attention multiples the queries by the keys, divides by a scaling factor and takes the softmax, and finally uses the result to compute a weighted sum of the values corresponding to the keys, generating an encoding of the original sequence.<ref name=\":0\" /> If <math>\\mathbf{Q}</math>, <math>\\mathbf{K}</math>, and <math>\\mathbf{V}</math> are the matrices containing the queries, keys, and values respectively and <math>n</math> is the dimension of the queries and keys, then the output of this attention mechanism is:<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{Attention}(\\mathbf{Q}, \\mathbf{K}, \\mathbf{V}) = \\text{softmax}(\\frac{\\mathbf{Q}\\mathbf{K}^T}{\\sqrt{n}})\\mathbf{V}\n\\end{align}\n</math>\n\nIn practice, it is useful to implement several attention mechanisms in parallel and then combine the resulting encodings together in a process called multi-head attention.\n\n== Training ==\nTransformers typically undergo [[semi-supervised learning]] involving [[Unsupervised learning|unsupervised]] pretraining followed by [[Supervised learning|supervised]] fine-tuning. Pretraining is typically done on a much larger dataset than fine-tuning, due to the restricted availability of labeled training data. Tasks for pretraining and fine-tuning commonly include:\n\n* next-sentence prediction<ref name=\":6\" />\n*[[question answering]]<ref name=\":7\" />\n*[[Natural-language understanding|reading comprehension]]\n*[[sentiment analysis]]<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alex|last2=Singh|first2=Amanpreet|last3=Michael|first3=Julian|last4=Hill|first4=Felix|last5=Levy|first5=Omer|last6=Bowman|first6=Samuel|date=2018|title=GLUE: A Multi-Task Benchmark and Analysis Platform for Natural Language Understanding|journal=Proceedings of the 2018 EMNLP Workshop BlackboxNLP: Analyzing and Interpreting Neural Networks for NLP|pages=353\u2013355|location=Stroudsburg, PA, USA|publisher=Association for Computational Linguistics|doi=10.18653/v1/w18-5446|bibcode=2018arXiv180407461W|arxiv=1804.07461}}</ref>\n*[[Text Summaries|paraphrasing]]<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Applications ==\nThe Transformer finds most of its applications in the field of [[natural language processing]] (NLP), for example the tasks of [[machine translation]] and [[Time series|time series prediction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/inside-machine-learning/what-is-a-transformer-d07dd1fbec04|title=What is a Transformer?|last=Allard|first=Maxime|date=2019-07-01|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>  Many pretrained models such as GPT-2, BERT, XLNet, and RoBERTa demonstrate the ability of Transformers to perform a wide variety of such NLP-related tasks, and have the potential to find real-world applications.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=XLNet: Generalized Autoregressive Pretraining for Language Understanding|last=Yang, Zhilin Dai, Zihang Yang, Yiming Carbonell, Jaime Salakhutdinov, Ruslan Le, Quoc V.|date=2019-06-19|oclc=1106350082}}</ref> These may include:\n\n* [[machine translation]]\n* [[Automatic summarization|document summarization]]\n* [[Natural-language generation|document generation]]\n* [[Named-entity recognition|named entity recognition]] (NER)<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@datamonsters/artificial-neural-networks-in-natural-language-processing-bcf62aa9151a|title=10 Applications of Artificial Neural Networks in Natural Language Processing|last=Monsters|first=Data|date=2017-09-26|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n* [[speech recognition]]<ref name=\":9\" />\n* [[sequence analysis | biological sequence analysis]] <ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1101/622803|title=Biological structure and function emerge from scaling unsupervised learning to 250 million protein sequences|year=2019|last1=Rives|first1=Alexander|last2=Goyal|first2=Siddharth|last3=Meier|first3=Joshua|last4=Guo|first4=Demi|last5=Ott|first5=Myle|last6=Zitnick|first6=C. Lawrence|last7=Ma|first7=Jerry|last8=Fergus|first8=Rob}}</ref>\n\n== References ==<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n<!-- Use the format: * [http://www.example.com/ example.com] -->\n<!--- Categories --->\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Long Short Term Memory}}\n[[Category:Artificial neural networks]]\n", "name_user": "Zeno Gantner", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transformer_(machine_learning_model)"}
{"title_page": "Angelica Ljungquist", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish volleyball player and coach}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name            = Angelica Ljungquist\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| caption         = \n| fullname        = \n| nickname        = \n| nationality     = {{flag|Sweden}}\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1974|12|20|mf=y}}                    \n| birth_place     =\n| death_date      = <!-- Use  {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}}   -->\n| death_place     = \n| hometown        = [[Vallentuna]], [[Sweden]]\n| height          = 6ft 3in\n| weight          = <!-- \"X kg\" or \"X lb\" (conversions are automatic) -->\n| spike           = <!-- \"X cm\" or \"X in\" (conversions are automatic) -->\n| block           = <!-- \"X cm\" or \"X in\" (conversions are automatic) -->\n| college         = [[Hawaii Rainbow Wahine volleyball|Hawai'i]]\n| position        = Middle blocker / Middle hitter\n| currentclub     =\n| currentnumber   = \n| years1          = \n| team1           =\n| nationalyears1  = \n| nationalteam1   = \n| medaltemplates  =\n| medals = \n| medaltemplates-expand = yes\n| updated         = \n}}'''Angelica Elsa Birgitta Ljungquist''' (now Angelica Ljungqvist)<ref>She now uses the traditional Swedish spelling of her name</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/05/03/sports/sports-breaking/celebrated-former-wahine-volleyballer-join-ah-mow-santos-staff/|title=Celebrated former Wahine volleyballer to join UH coaching staff|last=cluis@staradvertiser.com|first=By Cindy Luis|last2=May 3|first2=2017|date=2017-05-03|website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> (born December 20, 1974) is a Swedish volleyball coach, and former volleyball player, both at the amateur and professional level. She is the associate head coach for the [[Hawaii Rainbow Wahine volleyball|Rainbow Wahines]], the volleyball team for the University of Hawai'i at M\u0101noa.\n\n== Early years ==\nLjungquist was born December 20, 1974 to Ann-Britt and Leif Ljungquist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bvbinfo.com/player.asp?ID=4674|title=Angelica Ljungquist|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bvbinfo.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> She grew up in [[Vallentuna]], [[Sweden]], and graduated from Vallentuna Gymnasium ([[Stockholm]], Sweden) in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://volleybows.tripod.com/1996/roster/ljungquist.html|title=ANGELICA LJUNGQUIST|website=volleybows.tripod.com|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><br />\n\n== College ==\nLjungquist came to Hawai'i to play volleyball for the [[Hawaii Rainbow Wahine volleyball|Rainbow Wahines]] in 1993. She came to play for coach [[Dave Shoji]], who already had national championships in [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women championships#Volleyball|1979]] (AIAW), [[1982 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament|1982]], [[1983 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament|1983]], and [[1987 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament|1987]] (NCAA). She was talented enough to be named to All-American teams as a freshman, but [[Dave Shoji|Shoji]] could always find areas needing improvement. Ljungquist had difficulty getting her left hand over the net, so Shoji asked her how to say \"left\" in Swedish. She told him the word is \"v\u00e4nster\", so after that he would remonstrate \"v\u00e4nster, v\u00e4nster hand\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.honolulumagazine.com/Honolulu-Magazine/November-2014/Legendary-UH-Womens-Volleyball-Coach-Dave-Shoji-Recounts-Career-Highs-and-Lows-in-New-Book/|title=Legendary UH Women\u2019s Volleyball Coach Dave Shoji Recounts Career Highs and Lows in New Book|website=www.honolulumagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nShe not made All-American team as a freshman, she made All-American team all four years, the first player from Hawai'i to earn such a distinction.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/35457481/20-years-later-bond-brings-ljungqvist-back-to-rainbow-wahine-as-assistant-coach|title=20 years later, bond brings Ljungqvist back to Rainbow Wahine as assistant coach|last=Hatcher|first=Taryn|date=|website=hawaiinewsnow.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> In 1996, she helped lead the team to the title game of the [[1996 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament]]. She was named to the All- Tournament team.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ljungquist was named the Player of the Year in volleyball by the NCAA in 1996.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2002/05/07/sports/index.html|title=Honolulu Star-Bulletin Sports|website=archives.starbulletin.com|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> She was also named Player of the Year by Volleyball Magazine, and the [[American Volleyball Coaches Association|AVCA]] in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/05/03/sports/sports-breaking/celebrated-former-wahine-volleyballer-join-ah-mow-santos-staff/|title=Celebrated former Wahine volleyballer to join UH coaching staff|last=cluis@staradvertiser.com|first=By Cindy Luis|last2=May 3|first2=2017|date=2017-05-03|website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n\nIn 1997, Ljungquist won the Honda Award (now the [[Honda Sports Award]]) as the nation's best female volleyball player.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/hawaiiathletics1/docs/2012_wvb_media_guide_0816_with_covers/53|title=2012 Rainbow Wahine Volleyball Media Guide|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegiatewomensportsawards.com/archives/volleyball|title=Volleyball|website=CWSA|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== National team ==\nLjungquist played for Swedish National teams, the Swedish Indoor National Team from 1992-2006, and the Swedish Beach National Team from 2002-03 and 2007-10.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://hawaiiathletics.com/staff-directory/angelica-ljungqvist/556|title=Angelica Ljungqvist - Associate Coach - Staff Directory|website=University of Hawai'i at Manoa Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Professional teams ==\nShe played professionally on several teams in Europe, as well as Brazil, and Japan.<ref name=\":1\" /> She started her pro career indoors in Brazil in 1998, then in Turkey in 1999, then played for teams in Italy in 2000 and 2001 including Famili Imola in northern Italy.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Coaching ==\nWhen her college teammate, [[Robyn Ah Mow-Santos]], was hired by the Rainbow Wahine to be the new head coach of the volleyball team, one of the first people she contacted was Ljungquist. Ah Mow-Santos instant messaged Ljungquist even before she was offered the job, and asked Ljungquist to be on her staff. Ljungquist initially thought she was joking, but after realizing it was a serious request, agreed to join the coaching staff. She finished her law degree in Sweden, then returned to Hawai'i to become a coach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/35971392/how-friendship-and-facebook-brought-two-uh-all-americans-back-to-manoa-to-coach-the-rainbow-wahine|title=How friendship and Facebook brought two UH All-Americans back to Manoa to coach the Rainbow Wahine|last=Hatcher|first=Taryn|date=|website=hawaiinewsnow.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Honda Sports Award}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Middle blockers]]\n[[Category:Hawaii Rainbow Wahine volleyball coaches]]\n[[Category:American volleyball coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swedish volleyball player and coach}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name            = Angelica Ljungquis\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| caption         = \n| fullname        = \n| nickname        = \n| nationality     = {{flag|Sweden}}\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1974|12|20|mf=y}}                    \n| birth_place     =\n| death_date      = <!-- Use  {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}}   -->\n| death_place     = \n| hometown        = [[Vallentuna]], [[Sweden]]\n| height          = 6-3\n| weight          = <!-- \"X kg\" or \"X lb\" (conversions are automatic) -->\n| spike           = <!-- \"X cm\" or \"X in\" (conversions are automatic) -->\n| block           = <!-- \"X cm\" or \"X in\" (conversions are automatic) -->\n| college         = [[Hawaii Rainbow Wahine volleyball|Hawai'i]]\n| position        = Middle blocker / Middle hitter\n| currentclub     =\n| currentnumber   = \n| years1          = \n| team1           =\n| nationalyears1  = \n| nationalteam1   = \n| medaltemplates  =\n| medals = \n| medaltemplates-expand = yes\n| updated         = \n}}'''Angelica Elsa Birgitta Ljungquist''' (now Angelica Ljungqvist)<ref>She now uses the traditional Swedish spelling of her name</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/05/03/sports/sports-breaking/celebrated-former-wahine-volleyballer-join-ah-mow-santos-staff/|title=Celebrated former Wahine volleyballer to join UH coaching staff|last=cluis@staradvertiser.com|first=By Cindy Luis|last2=May 3|first2=2017|date=2017-05-03|website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> (born December 20, 1974) is a Swedish volleyball coach, and former volleyball player, both at the amateur and professional level. She is the associate head coach for the [[Hawaii Rainbow Wahine volleyball|Rainbow Wahines]], the volleyball team for the University of Hawai'i at M\u0101noa.\n\n== Early years ==\nLjungquist was born December 20, 1974 to Ann-Britt and Leif Ljungquist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bvbinfo.com/player.asp?ID=4674|title=Angelica Ljungquist|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bvbinfo.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> She grew up in [[Vallentuna]], [[Sweden]], and graduated from Vallentuna Gymnasium ([[Stockholm]], Sweden) in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://volleybows.tripod.com/1996/roster/ljungquist.html|title=ANGELICA LJUNGQUIST|website=volleybows.tripod.com|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><br />\n\n== College ==\nLjungquist came to Hawai'i to play volleyball for the [[Hawaii Rainbow Wahine volleyball|Rainbow Wahines]] in 1993. She came to play for coach [[Dave Shoji]], who already had national championships in [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women championships#Volleyball|1979]] (AIAW), [[1982 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament|1982]], [[1983 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament|1983]], and [[1987 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament|1987]] (NCAA). She was talented enough to be named to All-American teams as a freshman, but [[Dave Shoji|Shoji]] could always find areas needing improvement. Ljungquist had difficulty getting her left hand over the net, so Shoji asked her how to say \"left\" in Swedish. She told him the word is \"v\u00e4nster\", so after that he would remonstrate \"v\u00e4nster, v\u00e4nster hand\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.honolulumagazine.com/Honolulu-Magazine/November-2014/Legendary-UH-Womens-Volleyball-Coach-Dave-Shoji-Recounts-Career-Highs-and-Lows-in-New-Book/|title=Legendary UH Women\u2019s Volleyball Coach Dave Shoji Recounts Career Highs and Lows in New Book|website=www.honolulumagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nShe not made All-American team as a freshman, she made All-American team all four years, the first player from Hawai'i to earn such a distinction.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/35457481/20-years-later-bond-brings-ljungqvist-back-to-rainbow-wahine-as-assistant-coach|title=20 years later, bond brings Ljungqvist back to Rainbow Wahine as assistant coach|last=Hatcher|first=Taryn|date=|website=hawaiinewsnow.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> In 1996, she helped lead the team to the title game of the [[1996 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament]]. She was named to the All- Tournament team.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ljungquist was named the Player of the Year in volleyball by the NCAA in 1996.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2002/05/07/sports/index.html|title=Honolulu Star-Bulletin Sports|website=archives.starbulletin.com|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> She was also named Player of the Year by Volleyball Magazine, and the [[American Volleyball Coaches Association|AVCA]] in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/05/03/sports/sports-breaking/celebrated-former-wahine-volleyballer-join-ah-mow-santos-staff/|title=Celebrated former Wahine volleyballer to join UH coaching staff|last=cluis@staradvertiser.com|first=By Cindy Luis|last2=May 3|first2=2017|date=2017-05-03|website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n\nIn 1997, Ljungquist won the Honda Award (now the [[Honda Sports Award]]) as the nation's best female volleyball player.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/hawaiiathletics1/docs/2012_wvb_media_guide_0816_with_covers/53|title=2012 Rainbow Wahine Volleyball Media Guide|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegiatewomensportsawards.com/archives/volleyball|title=Volleyball|website=CWSA|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== National team ==\nLjungquist played for Swedish National teams, the Swedish Indoor National Team from 1992-2006, and the Swedish Beach National Team from 2002-03 and 2007-10.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://hawaiiathletics.com/staff-directory/angelica-ljungqvist/556|title=Angelica Ljungqvist - Associate Coach - Staff Directory|website=University of Hawai'i at Manoa Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Professional teams ==\nShe played professionally on several teams in Europe, as well as Brazil, and Japan.<ref name=\":1\" /> She started her pro career indoors in Brazil in 1998, then in Turkey in 1999, then played for teams in Italy in 2000 and 2001 including Famili Imola in northern Italy.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Coaching ==\nWhen her college teammate, [[Robyn Ah Mow-Santos]], was hired by the Rainbow Wahine to be the new head coach of the volleyball team, one of the first people she contacted was Ljungquist. Ah Mow-Santos instant messaged Ljungquist even before she was offered the job, and asked Ljungquist to be on her staff. Ljungquist initially thought she was joking, but after realizing it was a serious request, agreed to join the coaching staff. She finished her law degree in Sweden, then returned to Hawai'i to become a coach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/35971392/how-friendship-and-facebook-brought-two-uh-all-americans-back-to-manoa-to-coach-the-rainbow-wahine|title=How friendship and Facebook brought two UH All-Americans back to Manoa to coach the Rainbow Wahine|last=Hatcher|first=Taryn|date=|website=hawaiinewsnow.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Honda Sports Award}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Middle blockers]]\n[[Category:Hawaii Rainbow Wahine volleyball coaches]]\n[[Category:American volleyball coaches]]\n", "name_user": "Joseph2302", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angelica_Ljungquist"}
{"title_page": "Free Fire", "text_new": "{{About|2015 december 29 action comedy film|online multiplayer battle royale game|Garena Free Fire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Free Fire\n| image          = Free Fire.png\n| caption        = British release poster\n| director       = [[Ben Wheatley]]\n\n| producers      = Andy Starke\n| writers        = {{ubl|Amy Jump|Ben Wheatley}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sharlto Copley]]\n* [[Armie Hammer]]\n* [[Brie Larson]]\n* [[Cillian Murphy]]\n* [[Jack Reynor]]\n* [[Babou Ceesay]]\n* [[Enzo Cilenti]]\n* [[Sam Riley]]\n* [[Michael Smiley]]\n* [[Noah Taylor]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music          = {{ubl|[[Ben Salisbury]]|[[Geoff Barrow]]}}\n| cinematography = [[Laurie Rose (cinematographer)|Laurie Rose]]\n| editing        = {{ubl|Amy Jump|Ben Wheatley}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Film4 Productions]]\n* [[British Film Institute|BFI]]\n* Rook Films\n* Protagonist Pictures\n}}\n| distributor    = \n {{Plainlist|\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]] {{small|(United States)}}\n* [[StudioCanal UK]]\n}}\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|2016|9|8|[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2017|3|31|United Kingdom}}\n<!--DO NOT ADD U.S RELEASE DATE, THIS IS A BRITISH FILM DETERMINED BY PRODUCTION COMPANIES-->\n| runtime        = 90 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiff.net/films/free-fire/|title=Free Fire|publisher=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=29 August 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $7 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/simonthompson/2017/04/20/free-fall-director-ben-wheatley-talks-making-movies-for-7-million-and-u-k-tax-incentives/ |title='Free Fall' Director Ben Wheatley Talks Making Movies For $7 Million And U.K. Tax Incentives |work=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n| gross          = $3.8 million<ref name=NUM>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Free-Fire#tab=box-office |title=Free Fire (2016)|publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Free Fire''''' is a 2016 British [[black comedy]]-[[action film]] directed by [[Ben Wheatley]], from a screenplay by Wheatley and Amy Jump. It stars [[Sharlto Copley]], [[Armie Hammer]], [[Brie Larson]], [[Cillian Murphy]], [[Jack Reynor]], [[Babou Ceesay]], [[Enzo Cilenti]], [[Sam Riley]], [[Michael Smiley]] and [[Noah Taylor]].\n\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on 8 September 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/toronto-film-festival-adds-movies-by-leonardo-dicaprio-werner-herzog-marlon-brando/|title=Toronto Film Festival Adds Movies by Leonardo DiCaprio, Werner Herzog, Marlon Brando|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Steve|last=Pond|date=9 September 2016|accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref> and also served as the closer of the 2016 [[BFI London Film Festival]] on 16 October.<ref name=\"deadline01082016\">{{cite web|last1=Tartaglione|first1=Nancy|title=Ben Wheatley\u2019s \u2018Free Fire\u2019 To Close London Film Fest; Martin Scorsese Exec Produces|url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/free-fire-london-film-festival-closing-night-ben-wheatley-martin-scorsese-brie-larson-cillian-murphy-1201796325/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=1 August 2016|date=1 August 2016}}</ref> The film was theatrically released in the United Kingdom on 31 March 2017, by [[StudioCanal UK]], and in the United States on 21 April 2017, by [[A24 (company)|A24]].\n\n== Plot ==\nDriving to meet [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] members Chris ([[Cillian Murphy]]) and Frank ([[Michael Smiley]]), Stevo ([[Sam Riley]]) tells Bernie ([[Enzo Cilenti]]) that he was beaten up the previous day by the cousin of a woman he assaulted. The group meet outside a Boston warehouse with intermediary Justine ([[Brie Larson]]), and a representative, Ord ([[Armie Hammer]]), leads them inside. The group is there to buy guns from arms dealer Vernon ([[Sharlto Copley]]) and his associates, Martin ([[Babou Ceesay]]), Harry ([[Jack Reynor]]) and Gordon ([[Noah Taylor]]). Despite tensions between the two groups and the fact that Vernon supplied the wrong rifles, the weapons are unloaded from a van and Chris\u2019 group hands over the money in a briefcase.\n\nStevo realizes that Harry was the one who beat him up the day before, and refuses to go near him, irritating Frank. Harry eventually notices and lashes out at Stevo, furthering the tensions between the groups. Stevo seemingly apologises, but then brags about what he did to Harry's cousin. Infuriated, Harry shoots Stevo in the shoulder. Both groups split off and begin shooting at each other. Martin, who was holding the briefcase, is grazed by a bullet in the head. The briefcase now lies in the open, with Vernon attempting to coerce his men to get it.\n\nBernie is shot in the back by Vernon and dies. Soon, two men with rifles begin shooting at both groups. One of them, Jimmy ([[Mark Monero]]), is killed, and the other is recognised by Ord as Howie ([[Patrick Bergin]]), who explains that he was hired to kill everyone and take the money. Before Howie can reveal who hired him, he is shot dead by Chris's group. Chris, defending Justine, requests that Vernon's group let her go. Gordon crawls after her, intent on killing her.\n\nAs the shooting continues, a telephone rings in one of the offices. Realising that they can call for backup, Chris sends the wounded Frank to the office, pursued by a wounded Vernon. Gordon chases Justine to the warehouse entrance, but she manages to kill him. As Chris, Ord, Stevo and Harry engage in another shootout, Vernon is severely burned by a trap set by Frank but kills him as he reaches the phone.\n\nMartin regains consciousness, and begins deliriously shooting at his own group. He reveals that he planned to double-cross Vernon and hired Howie and Jimmy to kill the others. Martin gets the briefcase, but dies from his injuries. After getting past Ord and Harry, Chris reaches the office and kills Vernon. Using the phone to call his associates, Chris is cut off by Ord while Harry distracts Stevo. Returning to the warehouse, Justine takes Jimmy's rifle but passes out.\n\nOne of Chris's associates, Leary ([[Tom Davis (British actor)|Tom Davis]]), arrives at the warehouse in search of his IRA comrades, but is killed by Harry. Taking the briefcase, Harry attempts to escape in the van, fired at by Stevo and Ord. Harry runs over Stevo, killing him, but not before Stevo shoots him dead. The fire Frank caused spreads and the sprinklers come on. Exhausted and out of bullets, Ord and Chris agree to stop fighting, take the money, and attempt to escape before the inevitable arrival of the police.\n\nJustine shoots Ord in the head and Chris in the stomach. Lying on the ground, Chris tells Justine he regrets not having known her better as he begins to succumb to his wounds, and Justine reveals she was in on the double-cross with Martin. As Justine limps to the warehouse entrance with the money, the sound of sirens grows louder. When red and blue flashing lights appear under the bottom of the exit, Justine realizes although she survived, she will not escape.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Cillian Murphy]] as Chris\n* [[Armie Hammer]] as Ord\n* [[Brie Larson]] as Justine\n* [[Sharlto Copley]] as Vernon\n* [[Jack Reynor]] as Harry\n* [[Babou Ceesay]] as Martin\n* [[Enzo Cilenti]] as Bernie\n* [[Sam Riley]] as Stevo\n* [[Michael Smiley]] as Frank\n* [[Noah Taylor]] as Gordon\n* [[Patrick Bergin]] as Howie\n* [[Tom Davis (British actor)|Tom Davis]] as Leary\n* [[Mark Monero]] as Jimmy\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Production ==\nIn October 2014, [[Olivia Wilde]], [[Luke Evans (actor)|Luke Evans]], [[Armie Hammer]], [[Cillian Murphy]] and [[Michael Smiley]] joined the cast of the film, with [[Ben Wheatley]] set to direct from a screenplay he wrote with Amy Jump. Wheatley and Andy Starke produced under their Rook Films banner, and [[Film4 Productions]] produced and financed the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/luke-evans-to-star-in-ben-wheatleys-free-fire-1201338287/|title=Luke Evans to Star in Ben Wheatley\u2019s \u2018Free Fire\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Leo|last=Barraclough|date=24 October 2014|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> In April 2015, [[Brie Larson]] replaced Wilde, who had to drop out due to a schedule conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/brie-larson-free-fire-cast-olivia-wilde-ben-wheatley-1201468099/|title=Brie Larson Joins Cast of Ben Wheatley\u2019s \u2018Free Fire\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=7 April 2015|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began on 8 June 2015 in [[Brighton]], [[East Sussex]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jagernauth|first1=Kevin|title=Ben Wheatley's 'Free Fire' Starts Filming, Full Cast Confirmed|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/ben-wheatleys-free-fire-starts-filming-full-cast-confirmed-20150609|accessdate=13 June 2015|publisher=indiewire.com|date=9 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jaafar|first1=Ali|title=Ben Wheatley\u2019s \u2018Free Fire\u2019 Rounds Out Cast: Jack Reynor, Sam Riley And Noah Taylor All On Board|url=http://deadline.com/2015/06/ben-wheatley-free-fire-jack-reynor-sam-riley-noah-taylor-martin-scorsese-armie-hammer-cillian-murphy-1201439919/|accessdate=13 June 2015|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=9 June 2015}}</ref> Production concluded on 17 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-72015-daniel-radcliffe-starts-shooting-swiss-army-men-meryl-streep-finishes-florence-foster-jenkins/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723005058/http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-72015-daniel-radcliffe-starts-shooting-swiss-army-men-meryl-streep-finishes-florence-foster-jenkins/|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 July 2015|title=On the Set for 7/20/15: Daniel Radcliffe Starts Shooting \u2018Swiss Army Men\u2019, Meryl Streep Finishes \u2018Florence Foster Jenkins\u2019|website=SSN Insider|date=20 July 2015|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nMost of the film was shot in the former print hall of ''[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]]'' newspaper in [[Hollingbury]], Brighton.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Argus is given the Hollywood treatment|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/15194001.The_Argus_is_given_the_Hollywood_treatment/|website=The Argus|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Dock scenes were filmed at [[Shoreham-by-Sea|Shoreham Port]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Where was 'Free Fire' filmed?|url=http://www.british-film-locations.com/Free-Fire-2016|website=British Film Locations|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn February 2015, it was announced that [[StudioCanal]] had acquired distribution rights to the film in the United Kingdom, while [[Sony Pictures Worldwide Acquisitions]] had acquired the rights in Australia, New Zealand, Latin America, Scandinavia and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/global/berlin-sony-pictures-worldwide-strikes-deal-on-wheatleys-free-fire-exclusive-1201427825/|title=Berlin: Sony Pictures Worldwide Strikes Deal on Wheatley\u2019s \u2018Free Fire\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=John|last=Hopewell|date=8 February 2015|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> In November 2015, it was announced that [[Alchemy (company)|Alchemy]] had acquired United States distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/alchemy-closing-deal-ben-wheatley-martin-scorsese-brie-larson-armie-hammer-free-fire-afm-1201619000/|title=Alchemy Closes Deal For Ben Wheatley\u2019s White-Hot \u2018Free Fire\u2019 \u2013 AFM|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike & Ali|last=Fleming Jr and Jaafar|date=12 November 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> However, on 10 March 2016, in the wake of rumours of Alchemy's financial troubles, distribution of the film was bought by [[A24 (company)|A24]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/a24-brie-larson-action-thriller-free-fire-1201727431/|title=A24 Boards Brie Larson\u2019s Action-Thriller \u2018Free Fire\u2019|website=Variety|first=Dave|last= McNary|date=10 March 2016|accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], and served as the closing night film of the [[London Film Festival]], on 16 October 2016.<ref name=\"deadline01082016\"/> The film was released in the United Kingdom on 31 March 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screendaily.com/features/free-fire-ben-wheatley-firing-on-all-cylinders-set-report/5108791.article?blocktitle=FEATURES&contentID=43731|title='Free Fire': Ben Wheatley firing on all cylinders (set report)|website=[[Screen Daily]]|first=Michael|last=Rosser|date=30 August 2016|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> and in the United States on 21 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/brie-larson-free-fire-their-finest-land-of-mine-oscars-release-date-1201895019/|title=\u2018Their Finest\u2019, \u2018Free Fire\u2019 & \u2018Land Of Mine\u2019 Target New Dates|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=26 January 2017|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Free Fire'' grossed $1.4 million in the United States and Canada, and $1.2 million in other territories, for a total of $2.6 million.<ref name=NUM/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Free Fire'' opened alongside ''[[The Promise (2016 American film)|The Promise]]'', ''[[Born in China]]'', ''[[Unforgettable (2017 film)|Unforgettable]]'' and ''[[Phoenix Forgotten]]'', and was projected to gross around $3 million from 1,070 cinemas in its opening weekend.<ref name=preview>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/box-office-fate-of-the-furious-unforgettable-1202347619/|title=Box Office: \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 to Get Burned by \u2018Fate of the Furious\u2019 |date=19 April 2017 |work=Variety}}</ref> However, it ended up debuting to $994,430, finishing 17th at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2017&wknd=16&p=.htm |title=Weekend Box Office Results for April 21-23, 2017|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Free Fire'' has an approval rating of 69%, based on 205 reviews, with an average rating of 6.3/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Free Fire'' aims squarely for genre thrills, and hits its target repeatedly and with great gusto\u2014albeit with something less than pure cinematic grace.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/free_fire |title=Free Fire (2016) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted average to reviews, the film has a score of 63 out of 100, based on 39 critics, indicating \"generally favourable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/free-fire |title=Free Fire Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n*[https://www.cuteskills.site/2019/12/free-fire-hack-script-unlimited-diamonds.html free fire hack script unlimited diamonds]\n\n{{Ben Wheatley}}\n{{TIFF People's Choice Midnight Madness}}\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s black comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime comedy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British action comedy films]]\n[[Category:British black comedy films]]\n[[Category:British crime comedy films]]\n[[Category:British comedy thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about arms trafficking]]\n[[Category:Films about violence]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ben Wheatley]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Films shot in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Film4 Productions films]]\n[[Category:Girls with guns films]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|2015 december 29 action comedy film|online multiplayer battle royale game|Garena Free Fire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Free Fire\n| image          = Free Fire.png\n| caption        = British release poster\n| director       = [[Ben Wheatley]]\n\n| producers      = Andy Starke\n| writers        = {{ubl|Amy Jump|Ben Wheatley}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sharlto Copley]]\n* [[Armie Hammer]]\n* [[Brie Larson]]\n* [[Cillian Murphy]]\n* [[Jack Reynor]]\n* [[Babou Ceesay]]\n* [[Enzo Cilenti]]\n* [[Sam Riley]]\n* [[Michael Smiley]]\n* [[Noah Taylor]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music          = {{ubl|[[Ben Salisbury]]|[[Geoff Barrow]]}}\n| cinematography = [[Laurie Rose (cinematographer)|Laurie Rose]]\n| editing        = {{ubl|Amy Jump|Ben Wheatley}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Film4 Productions]]\n* [[British Film Institute|BFI]]\n* Rook Films\n* Protagonist Pictures\n}}\n| distributor    = \n {{Plainlist|\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]] {{small|(United States)}}\n* [[StudioCanal UK]]\n}}\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|2016|9|8|[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2017|3|31|United Kingdom}}\n<!--DO NOT ADD U.S RELEASE DATE, THIS IS A BRITISH FILM DETERMINED BY PRODUCTION COMPANIES-->\n| runtime        = 90 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiff.net/films/free-fire/|title=Free Fire|publisher=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=29 August 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $7 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/simonthompson/2017/04/20/free-fall-director-ben-wheatley-talks-making-movies-for-7-million-and-u-k-tax-incentives/ |title='Free Fall' Director Ben Wheatley Talks Making Movies For $7 Million And U.K. Tax Incentives |work=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n| gross          = $3.8 million<ref name=NUM>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Free-Fire#tab=box-office |title=Free Fire (2016)|publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Free Fire''''' is a 2016 British [[black comedy]]-[[action film]] directed by [[Ben Wheatley]], from a screenplay by Wheatley and Amy Jump. It stars [[Sharlto Copley]], [[Armie Hammer]], [[Brie Larson]], [[Cillian Murphy]], [[Jack Reynor]], [[Babou Ceesay]], [[Enzo Cilenti]], [[Sam Riley]], [[Michael Smiley]] and [[Noah Taylor]].\n\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on 8 September 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/toronto-film-festival-adds-movies-by-leonardo-dicaprio-werner-herzog-marlon-brando/|title=Toronto Film Festival Adds Movies by Leonardo DiCaprio, Werner Herzog, Marlon Brando|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Steve|last=Pond|date=9 September 2016|accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref> and also served as the closer of the 2016 [[BFI London Film Festival]] on 16 October.<ref name=\"deadline01082016\">{{cite web|last1=Tartaglione|first1=Nancy|title=Ben Wheatley\u2019s \u2018Free Fire\u2019 To Close London Film Fest; Martin Scorsese Exec Produces|url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/free-fire-london-film-festival-closing-night-ben-wheatley-martin-scorsese-brie-larson-cillian-murphy-1201796325/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=1 August 2016|date=1 August 2016}}</ref> The film was theatrically released in the United Kingdom on 31 March 2017, by [[StudioCanal UK]], and in the United States on 21 April 2017, by [[A24 (company)|A24]].\n\n== Plot ==\nDriving to meet [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] members Chris ([[Cillian Murphy]]) and Frank ([[Michael Smiley]]), Stevo ([[Sam Riley]]) tells Bernie ([[Enzo Cilenti]]) that he was beaten up the previous day by the cousin of a woman he assaulted. The group meet outside a Boston warehouse with intermediary Justine ([[Brie Larson]]), and a representative, Ord ([[Armie Hammer]]), leads them inside. The group is there to buy guns from arms dealer Vernon ([[Sharlto Copley]]) and his associates, Martin ([[Babou Ceesay]]), Harry ([[Jack Reynor]]) and Gordon ([[Noah Taylor]]). Despite tensions between the two groups and the fact that Vernon supplied the wrong rifles, the weapons are unloaded from a van and Chris\u2019 group hands over the money in a briefcase.\n\nStevo realizes that Harry was the one who beat him up the day before, and refuses to go near him, irritating Frank. Harry eventually notices and lashes out at Stevo, furthering the tensions between the groups. Stevo seemingly apologises, but then brags about what he did to Harry's cousin. Infuriated, Harry shoots Stevo in the shoulder. Both groups split off and begin shooting at each other. Martin, who was holding the briefcase, is grazed by a bullet in the head. The briefcase now lies in the open, with Vernon attempting to coerce his men to get it.\n\nBernie is shot in the back by Vernon and dies. Soon, two men with rifles begin shooting at both groups. One of them, Jimmy ([[Mark Monero]]), is killed, and the other is recognised by Ord as Howie ([[Patrick Bergin]]), who explains that he was hired to kill everyone and take the money. Before Howie can reveal who hired him, he is shot dead by Chris's group. Chris, defending Justine, requests that Vernon's group let her go. Gordon crawls after her, intent on killing her.\n\nAs the shooting continues, a telephone rings in one of the offices. Realising that they can call for backup, Chris sends the wounded Frank to the office, pursued by a wounded Vernon. Gordon chases Justine to the warehouse entrance, but she manages to kill him. As Chris, Ord, Stevo and Harry engage in another shootout, Vernon is severely burned by a trap set by Frank but kills him as he reaches the phone.\n\nMartin regains consciousness, and begins deliriously shooting at his own group. He reveals that he planned to double-cross Vernon and hired Howie and Jimmy to kill the others. Martin gets the briefcase, but dies from his injuries. After getting past Ord and Harry, Chris reaches the office and kills Vernon. Using the phone to call his associates, Chris is cut off by Ord while Harry distracts Stevo. Returning to the warehouse, Justine takes Jimmy's rifle but passes out.\n\nOne of Chris's associates, Leary ([[Tom Davis (British actor)|Tom Davis]]), arrives at the warehouse in search of his IRA comrades, but is killed by Harry. Taking the briefcase, Harry attempts to escape in the van, fired at by Stevo and Ord. Harry runs over Stevo, killing him, but not before Stevo shoots him dead. The fire Frank caused spreads and the sprinklers come on. Exhausted and out of bullets, Ord and Chris agree to stop fighting, take the money, and attempt to escape before the inevitable arrival of the police.\n\nJustine shoots Ord in the head and Chris in the stomach. Lying on the ground, Chris tells Justine he regrets not having known her better as he begins to succumb to his wounds, and Justine reveals she was in on the double-cross with Martin. As Justine limps to the warehouse entrance with the money, the sound of sirens grows louder. When red and blue flashing lights appear under the bottom of the exit, Justine realizes although she survived, she will not escape.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Cillian Murphy]] as Chris\n* [[Armie Hammer]] as Ord\n* [[Brie Larson]] as Justine\n* [[Sharlto Copley]] as Vernon\n* [[Jack Reynor]] as Harry\n* [[Babou Ceesay]] as Martin\n* [[Enzo Cilenti]] as Bernie\n* [[Sam Riley]] as Stevo\n* [[Michael Smiley]] as Frank\n* [[Noah Taylor]] as Gordon\n* [[Patrick Bergin]] as Howie\n* [[Tom Davis (British actor)|Tom Davis]] as Leary\n* [[Mark Monero]] as Jimmy\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Production ==\nIn October 2014, [[Olivia Wilde]], [[Luke Evans (actor)|Luke Evans]], [[Armie Hammer]], [[Cillian Murphy]] and [[Michael Smiley]] joined the cast of the film, with [[Ben Wheatley]] set to direct from a screenplay he wrote with Amy Jump. Wheatley and Andy Starke produced under their Rook Films banner, and [[Film4 Productions]] produced and financed the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/luke-evans-to-star-in-ben-wheatleys-free-fire-1201338287/|title=Luke Evans to Star in Ben Wheatley\u2019s \u2018Free Fire\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Leo|last=Barraclough|date=24 October 2014|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> In April 2015, [[Brie Larson]] replaced Wilde, who had to drop out due to a schedule conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/brie-larson-free-fire-cast-olivia-wilde-ben-wheatley-1201468099/|title=Brie Larson Joins Cast of Ben Wheatley\u2019s \u2018Free Fire\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=7 April 2015|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] on the film began on 8 June 2015 in [[Brighton]], [[East Sussex]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jagernauth|first1=Kevin|title=Ben Wheatley's 'Free Fire' Starts Filming, Full Cast Confirmed|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/ben-wheatleys-free-fire-starts-filming-full-cast-confirmed-20150609|accessdate=13 June 2015|publisher=indiewire.com|date=9 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jaafar|first1=Ali|title=Ben Wheatley\u2019s \u2018Free Fire\u2019 Rounds Out Cast: Jack Reynor, Sam Riley And Noah Taylor All On Board|url=http://deadline.com/2015/06/ben-wheatley-free-fire-jack-reynor-sam-riley-noah-taylor-martin-scorsese-armie-hammer-cillian-murphy-1201439919/|accessdate=13 June 2015|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=9 June 2015}}</ref> Production concluded on 17 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-72015-daniel-radcliffe-starts-shooting-swiss-army-men-meryl-streep-finishes-florence-foster-jenkins/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723005058/http://www.ssninsider.com/on-the-set-for-72015-daniel-radcliffe-starts-shooting-swiss-army-men-meryl-streep-finishes-florence-foster-jenkins/|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 July 2015|title=On the Set for 7/20/15: Daniel Radcliffe Starts Shooting \u2018Swiss Army Men\u2019, Meryl Streep Finishes \u2018Florence Foster Jenkins\u2019|website=SSN Insider|date=20 July 2015|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nMost of the film was shot in the former print hall of ''[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]]'' newspaper in [[Hollingbury]], Brighton.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Argus is given the Hollywood treatment|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/15194001.The_Argus_is_given_the_Hollywood_treatment/|website=The Argus|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Dock scenes were filmed at [[Shoreham-by-Sea|Shoreham Port]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Where was 'Free Fire' filmed?|url=http://www.british-film-locations.com/Free-Fire-2016|website=British Film Locations|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn February 2015, it was announced that [[StudioCanal]] had acquired distribution rights to the film in the United Kingdom, while [[Sony Pictures Worldwide Acquisitions]] had acquired the rights in Australia, New Zealand, Latin America, Scandinavia and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/global/berlin-sony-pictures-worldwide-strikes-deal-on-wheatleys-free-fire-exclusive-1201427825/|title=Berlin: Sony Pictures Worldwide Strikes Deal on Wheatley\u2019s \u2018Free Fire\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=John|last=Hopewell|date=8 February 2015|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> In November 2015, it was announced that [[Alchemy (company)|Alchemy]] had acquired United States distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/alchemy-closing-deal-ben-wheatley-martin-scorsese-brie-larson-armie-hammer-free-fire-afm-1201619000/|title=Alchemy Closes Deal For Ben Wheatley\u2019s White-Hot \u2018Free Fire\u2019 \u2013 AFM|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike & Ali|last=Fleming Jr and Jaafar|date=12 November 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> However, on 10 March 2016, in the wake of rumours of Alchemy's financial troubles, distribution of the film was bought by [[A24 (company)|A24]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/a24-brie-larson-action-thriller-free-fire-1201727431/|title=A24 Boards Brie Larson\u2019s Action-Thriller \u2018Free Fire\u2019|website=Variety|first=Dave|last= McNary|date=10 March 2016|accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], and served as the closing night film of the [[London Film Festival]], on 16 October 2016.<ref name=\"deadline01082016\"/> The film was released in the United Kingdom on 31 March 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screendaily.com/features/free-fire-ben-wheatley-firing-on-all-cylinders-set-report/5108791.article?blocktitle=FEATURES&contentID=43731|title='Free Fire': Ben Wheatley firing on all cylinders (set report)|website=[[Screen Daily]]|first=Michael|last=Rosser|date=30 August 2016|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> and in the United States on 21 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/brie-larson-free-fire-their-finest-land-of-mine-oscars-release-date-1201895019/|title=\u2018Their Finest\u2019, \u2018Free Fire\u2019 & \u2018Land Of Mine\u2019 Target New Dates|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=26 January 2017|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Free Fire'' grossed $1.4 million in the United States and Canada, and $1.2 million in other territories, for a total of $2.6 million.<ref name=NUM/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Free Fire'' opened alongside ''[[The Promise (2016 American film)|The Promise]]'', ''[[Born in China]]'', ''[[Unforgettable (2017 film)|Unforgettable]]'' and ''[[Phoenix Forgotten]]'', and was projected to gross around $3 million from 1,070 cinemas in its opening weekend.<ref name=preview>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/box-office-fate-of-the-furious-unforgettable-1202347619/|title=Box Office: \u2018Unforgettable\u2019 to Get Burned by \u2018Fate of the Furious\u2019 |date=19 April 2017 |work=Variety}}</ref> However, it ended up debuting to $994,430, finishing 17th at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2017&wknd=16&p=.htm |title=Weekend Box Office Results for April 21-23, 2017|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Free Fire'' has an approval rating of 69%, based on 205 reviews, with an average rating of 6.3/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Free Fire'' aims squarely for genre thrills, and hits its target repeatedly and with great gusto\u2014albeit with something less than pure cinematic grace.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/free_fire |title=Free Fire (2016) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted average to reviews, the film has a score of 63 out of 100, based on 39 critics, indicating \"generally favourable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/free-fire |title=Free Fire Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|4158096}}\n\n{{Ben Wheatley}}\n{{TIFF People's Choice Midnight Madness}}\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s black comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime comedy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British action comedy films]]\n[[Category:British black comedy films]]\n[[Category:British crime comedy films]]\n[[Category:British comedy thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about arms trafficking]]\n[[Category:Films about violence]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ben Wheatley]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Films shot in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Film4 Productions films]]\n[[Category:Girls with guns films]]\n", "name_user": "Moazzamzee", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_Fire"}
